<annotation text="Summary This paper re-examines the relationships between short term capital flows and monetary policy, in the light of a new theoretical approach of the forward exchange market. They contend that the traditional forward exchange market theory is a misleading one as it fails to give all the importance it deserves to the distinction between covered and uncovered exchange transactions and to the actual role of the ‘arbitrageurs.’ As a consequence of this analysis, they demonstrate that the problem of monetary management in an open economy must be dealt with in a way different from what has been usual, and they conclude that monetary policy, central banks&apos; intervention on the foreign exchange market and direct controls on capital movements can still have some efficiency in the struggle against inflation, either of the ‘domestic’ or the ‘imported’ type.">
